<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-quadratic_formula" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
	Find the <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of a quadratic function
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
  
  <title>The Quadratic Formula</title>
  <p>
    A point <m>(x,0)</m> in the Cartesian plane is an <xref ref="def-x_intercept" text="title"/> for the quadratic function <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> if the first coordinate is a solution to the <term>quadratic equation</term>
    <idx>
      <h>Equation</h>
      <h>Quadratic</h>
    </idx>
    <me>0 = ax^2 + bx + c.</me>
    To find the solutions to a quadratic equation, we use the final form from <xref ref="alg-completing_the_square" text="title"/> to rewrite the equation as
    <me>0 = ax^2 + bx + c = a\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 - \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a}</me>
    and solve this equation for <m>x</m>
    <md>
      <mrow>0 \amp= a\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 - \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a} \amp\amp \text{Add}\ \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a}\ \text{to both sides}</mrow>
      <mrow>a\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 \amp= \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a} \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ a</mrow>
      <mrow>\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 \amp= \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a^2} \amp\amp \text{Take the square root of both sides}</mrow>
      <mrow>x + \frac{b}{2a} \amp= \pm\sqrt{\frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a^2}} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
      <mrow>x + \frac{b}{2a} \amp= \pm\frac{\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{\sqrt{4a^2}} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
      <mrow>x + \frac{b}{2a} \amp= \frac{\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \amp\amp \text{Subtract}\ \frac{b}{2a}\ \text{from both sides}</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp= - \frac{b}{2a} + \frac{\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp= \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    It is important to note that these solutions are real numbers only when <m>b^2 - 4ac</m> is a non-negative number.
    This is an important invariant of a quadratic function.
  </p>
  
  <definition xml:id="def-discriminant">
    <title>The Discriminant</title>
    <p>
      The <term>discriminant</term>
      <idx>
	<h>Function</h>
	<h>Quadratic</h>
	<h>Discriminant</h>
      </idx>
      of the quadratic function <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> is the number
      <me>D = b^2 - 4ac</me>
    </p>
  </definition>

  <p>
    The discriminant provides both algebraic and geometric information about quadratic functions.
    On the algebraic side, the discriminant tells us how many solutions there are to the quadratic equation
    <m>ax^2 + bx  +c = 0</m>.
  </p>
  
  <claim xml:id="quadratic_formula">
    <title>The Quadratic Formula</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
	The quadratic equation
	<me>ax + bx + c = 0</me>
	has either two, one, or zero real solutions, depending on the <xref ref="def-discriminant" text="title"/>, <m>D = b^2 - 4ac</m>.
	<ol>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>D > 0</m>, then the two solutions are
	      <me>x = \frac{-b + \sqrt{D}}{2a}
	      \quad\text{and}\quad
	      x = \frac{-b - \sqrt{D}}{2a}.</me>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    If <m>D = 0</m>, then the only solution is
	    <me>x = \frac{-b + \sqrt{D}}{2a} = \frac{-b}{2a}.</me>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    If <m>D \lt 0</m>, then there are no real solutions.
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </claim>

  <p>
    On the geometric side, the discriminant tells us how many <m>x</m>-intercepts the graph of <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> has.
  </p>
  
  <theorem>
    <title>The <m>x</m>-intercepts of a Quadratic Function</title>
    <p>
      The quadratic function <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> has either two, one, or zero <m>x</m>-intercepts, depending on the <xref ref="def-discriminant" text="title"/>, <m>D = b^2 - 4ac</m>.
      <ol>
	<li>
	  <p>
	    If <m>D > 0</m>, then there are two <m>x</m>-intercepts,
	    <me>\left(\frac{-b + \sqrt{D}}{2a},0\right)
	    \quad\text{and}\quad
	    \left(\frac{-b - \sqrt{D}}{2a},\right).</me>
	  </p>
	</li>
	<li>
	  If <m>D = 0</m>, then there is one <m>x</m>-intercept
	  <me>\left(\frac{-b}{2a},0\right).</me>
	  Note this is the vertex.
	</li>
	<li>
	  If <m>D \lt 0</m>, then there are no <m>x</m>-intercepts.
	</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </theorem>
